eir usage.%0a%3c %0a%3c The use of filler words and sounds also has a psychological component, in which the recipient of speech is primed towards certain objects of notice through the use of a filler word or sound. A study which analyzed recipient behavior towards filler words and sounds found that listeners of speech will automatically keep track of filler words and sounds as a primer for where to focus attention. For example, if the filler word appears before a common object in the conversation, listeners would automatically gaze towards the object when the filler word was used by the speaker. Additionally, listeners would adapt to different speakers, and the psychological priming component was dependent on high or low frequency words, as well as the disfluency of the speaker as a determiner of whether to track attention after the use of a filler word. %0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/03/190306100641.htm%0a%3c %0a%3c https://blogs.transparent.com/english/um-uh-mm-and-the-use-of-filler-sounds-and-words/%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
